The course is comprised of interactive lectures and seminars designed to provide a multidisciplinary introduction to Ukraine and its recent socio-political changes, with a special focus on Ukraine's resilience in countering Russia's invasion and prospects for the future.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course aims to introduce Ukraine from different perspectives (historical, political,
sociological, cultural, media and digital studies), examine Ukraine's resilience in countering Russia's invasion, and reflect on Ukraine's role in contemporary Europe and the world.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Upon successful completion of the course, student should be able to: * understand and explain the socio-political situation in contemporary Ukraine as well as its historical and institutional preconditions; * analyze recent developments in Ukraine through historical, political, sociological, and other perspectives; * critically assess various discourses of Ukraine, its history, culture, society, politics etc. and understand the reasons behind them; * compare the Ukrainian case with developments in other countries; * locate Ukraine within European and global international structures; * conduct an independent academic, applied or policy study on Ukraine.
